The graph shown is a visual representation of the Thomae's function, also known as the popcorn function. This function is defined as:

\[ f(x) = \begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{q} & \text{if } x = \frac{p}{q} \text{ is a rational number in lowest terms} \\
0 & \text{if } x \text{ is irrational} 
\end{cases} \]

The function is discontinuous at every rational point and continuous at every irrational point. Therefore, the function is not continuous across all points. The premise of the question is correct, and the function is indeed not continuous everywhere.
